<TEXT type="str">If I had to sum up M. Night Shyamalan’s “Split” in one sentence, I would say it has personality. Lots of personality. 
 
The psychological thriller is about Casey, Claire and Marcia (Anya Taylor-Joy, Haley Lu Richardson and Jessica Sula), three high school girls who are kidnapped. Their assailant is Kevin Crumb, a man with dissociative identity disorder, resulting in 23 separate identities in one body. 
 
James McAvoy, who plays Kevin — and Dennis, Patricia and the rest of Kevin’s “alters” — shows off his extensive acting abilities as he plays multiple characters mostly through voice and body language alone. The switches in demeanor are almost reminiscent of a theater-character exercise, they are so quickly and drastically portrayed. 
 
The dissociative personality disorder isn’t the twist of “Split,” though; revealed from the start, it is not one of the many surprises that await. 
 
Kevin’s therapist Dr. Fletcher (Betty Buckley) sprinkles exposition by the handful throughout the movie, but also provides another layer of character that the film sorely needed. Out of the three kidnapped girls. Casey is the most fleshed out, her backstory being revealed through tasteful flashbacks. 
 
