For the first half of the movie, tension was evenly balanced, the creeping confusion of the unknown perfectly interspersed with laughable moments. The second half was where it fell flat. “Split” felt choppy and hurriedly borrowed from common horror movies. 
 
The movie is rated PG-13, yet presented its main actresses unnecessarily half-dressed for a good portion of the feature. I had high hopes for great character development, but whether it was too tight of a script or just bad writing, there was simply no room for growth. 
 
Yet the near absence of gore was a refreshing breath of air in the otherwise blood-soaked horror industry. An appropriately balanced score added to the atmosphere of “Split,” and good cinematography brought the tone of the movie to a suspenseful simmer. 
 
Overall, I would say that “Split” is a film best for watching at home with friends and cheap pizza. The movie wasn’t bad by any means, but as I watched the end credits roll, I felt unsatisfied. 
 
The only explanation I can think of is that the hype surrounding “Split” was just too great, and I had mistakenly expected more from the film. 
 
Annika Hinman is a senior at Venture High School. She enjoys reading, writing and listening to music. Email her at anonymous.annika@gmail.com.</TEXT> 
